          'Ripple filtering: capacitors in parallel with the load charge during voltage peaks and discharge between peaks, smoothing the output. A larger capacitor holds more charge and provides better smoothing. In practice, UPS systems use very large electrolytic capacitors (thousands of microfarads) plus inductors to form L-C filters that minimize ripple to acceptable levels.',
          'Practical considerations: rectifier diodes and SCRs must be rated for peak inverse voltage (PIV) — the maximum reverse voltage they must withstand. For 480V AC, PIV on diodes can exceed 1000V. Power diodes and SCRs get hot under load and require heatsinks. Failures often show as burnt components, damaged thermal paste, or overheated heatsinks. These should be noted and reported during maintenance visits.',
