          'Basic inverter operation: semiconductor switches (IGBTs, MOSFETs) rapidly switch the DC bus voltage on and off in a pattern that, when filtered, approximates a sine wave. This switching action is called Pulse Width Modulation (PWM). The switching frequency is typically 5-20kHz — much higher than the 60Hz output frequency, making it easier to filter.',
          'Inverter output parameters: voltage (e.g., 120V, 208V, 480V), frequency (60Hz), THD (total harmonic distortion, ideally <5%), crest factor (peak-to-RMS ratio, target ≈ 1.414 for true sine), and voltage regulation (±1-2% of nominal at steady load). The inverter should maintain these parameters regardless of load changes.',
